 highlighting the influence of radio, documentaries, and television. She explores how first-person or third-person narration really affects a film, in terms of genre conventions, viewer identification, time and nostalgia, subjectivity, and reliability. In conclusion she argues that voice-over increases film's potential for intimacy and sophisticated irony.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aChildren's literaturexTranslating. 0aChildren's literaturexTranslationsxHistory and criticism. 0aMotion picture plays, AmericanxHistory and criticism. 0aMotion pictureszUnited States. 0aTranslating and interpreting. 0aVoice-overs. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / Film & Video / General.2bisacsh  aadaptation theory.  aadaptations.  aall about eve.  aannie hall.  abarry lyndon.  abook to movie.  adocumentary film.  adouble indemnity.  aexposition.  afilm adaptation.  afilm criticism.  afilm interpretation.  afilm studies.  afilm technique.  afilm theory.  afilm.  afilmmaking.  ahow green was my valley.  aliterature.  amedia.  anaked city.  anarration.  anarrative theory.  anarrative.  anewsreels.  anonfiction.  aopening frames.  aplatoon.  apopular culture.  aradio.  ared river.  asilent film.  astorytelling.  atelevision.  atv.  avoice over.  awuthering heights.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Package Archive Pre-2000z978311063534840uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052090966340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520909663423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520909663/original  a978-3-11-063534-8  University of California Press Package Archive Pre-2000b2000  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-UCY